## 3. Interpretation

Traditional paradigms often treat morality as:

- Binary (saved/damned) or
- Static (saint/sinner)

MODAC reframes redemption as:

- A gradient field
- A noisy optimization process
- A return path rather than an escape hatch
- A limit-based sanctification instead of moral absolutism

**The defining virtue is not purity. It is trajectory.**

-----

## 4. Archetypal Mapping

MODAC aligns with five global narrative archetypes:

|Archetype   |Phase              |Basin Escape Mechanism                           |
|------------|-------------------|-------------------------------------------------|
|**Moses**   |Exile ‚Üí Law        |Pride (murder) ‚Üí Humility (stammering leadership)|
|**Odysseus**|Wandering ‚Üí Home   |Hubris (Troy boast) ‚Üí Nostos (cunning patience)  |
|**David**   |Trial ‚Üí Kingship   |Lust (Bathsheba) ‚Üí Penitence (Psalm 51)          |
|**Arjuna**  |Paralysis ‚Üí Action |Attachment (family grief) ‚Üí Dharma (duty clarity)|
|**Christ**  |Wilderness ‚Üí Return|Temptation (kingdoms) ‚Üí Sacrifice (Gethsemane)   |

MODAC asserts these are not myths of compliance‚Äîbut **models of return**.

Each archetype demonstrates a specific vice-attractor ‚Üí virtue-basin trajectory governed by the core equation.

